<DATE1>  30 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Radio Details `Majdal Shams First' Offer </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Radio Details `Majdal Shams First' Offer </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA3004092694 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el Hebrew 0700 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA3004092694 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el Hebrew 0700 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Druze leaders on the Golan Heights and in the 
Galilee have urged the Israeli Government, if its transfers 
Druze villages to Syria as part of a settlement, not to 
differentiate between the villages. 
  Our correspondent Hayim Hecht notes that on the map prepared 
by the IDF [Israel Defense Forces] within the framework of the 
plan called Majdal Shams First, three Druze villages -- Majdal 
Shams, Mas'adah, and Buq'ata -- will be transferred to the 
Syrians, while 'Ayn Qunyah, which is situated on lower terrain, 
will remain with Israel. 
  The Druze are demanding that the villages not be divided up 
and that all the lands that belong to them be transferred to 
Syria. Several Druze families on the Golan Heights have bought 
land in various locations in the Galilee in order to move there 
if the Golan is returned to Syria. Other Druze families are 
looking into that possibility and also the prospect of buying 
land on the Karmel. Our correspondent notes that Druze leaders 
are helping the Golan Druze. 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 0705 GMT on 30 April in 
a similar, but longer, report on the proposal adds: "Mt. Hermon 
and the road leading up to it, will of course remain under 
Israeli control. Israel is offering al-Asad two options, the 
first of course, preferable to us: Take the Druze villages 
first, we tell him, without the move being preceded by a 
pronouncement that we are conceding our sovereignty over the 
Golan Heights. The Israeli carrot to that option is a readiness 
to implement it immediately within three months. Al-Asad is a 
tough customer, therefore it is more reasonable that he will 
prefer the second option: The word first will be fortified by a 
Knesset resolution which recognizes Syrian sovereignty over the 
entire Golan Heights. What will sweeten Rabin's bitter pill is 
the fact that not a single Israeli settlement will be evacuated, 
just as in Gaza and Jericho First."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

