<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-084 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Secretary Warren Christoper Arrives in Damascus </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Secretary Warren Christoper Arrives in Damascus </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    More on al-Asad, Delegation Talks </H4>

<F P=102> JN0205053294 Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network in 
Arabic 0415 GMT 2 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN0205053294 </F>
<F P=104>  Damascus Syrian Arab Republic Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Hafiz al-Asad received U.S. Secretary of 
State Warren Christopher and his delegation yesterday evening. 
The delegation includes Dennis Ross, special Middle East peace 
process coordinator; Christopher Ross, U.S. ambassador in 
Damascus; and Martin Indyk, special assistant to the U.S. 
president for Middle East affairs. The meeting was attended by 
Faruq al-Shar', minister of foreign affairs; Muwaffaq al-'Allaf, 
head of the Syrian delegation to the peace talks; and Walid 
al-Mu'allim, Syria's ambassador in Washington. 
  Talks dealt with the peace process and all aspects of the 
ideas presented during Saturday's meeting. The president 
explained Syria's viewpoint, which stems from a real desire for 
a just and comprehensive peace that guarantees the rights of all 
parties. He stressed that addressing the basic peace issues is 
what can guarantee the progress of this process. 
  U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher and his 
delegation 
left Damascus last night following a two-day visit to the Syrian 
Arab Republic. Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar', senior Foreign 
Ministry officials, the Syrian ambassador in Washington, and the 
American ambassador in Damascus saw him off at Damascus 
International airport. 
  Speaking to reporters prior to his departure, Mr. 
Christopher 
described his talks with President Hafiz al-Asad as extremely 
serious and substantial. He said that, in his opinion, there is 
much to do and substantive talks to be held. A great deal of 
work and effort are awaiting us in the future, he said. 
  Mr. Christopher said he relayed some ideas to Damascus and 
took others from it. He told reporters he was going to Israel 
to meet with Yitzhaq Rabin and then on to Cairo. He said that 
at present he has no plans to return to Damascus and added that 
his country will play a more effective role to help the parties. 
He said he discussed the subject of bilateral relations with 
Foreign Minister Faruq al-Shar' and that he will resume talks 
with him if Mr. al- Shar' visits Washington. 
  Replying to a reporter's question, Foreign Minister Faruq 
al-Shar' said Syria does not accept phased peace with Israel and 
insists on complete withdrawal from the occupied Arab 
territories as a condition for the establishment of peace in the 
region. He added that there has been no change whatsoever in 
the Syrian position on the peace process. Al-Shar' said 
President Hafiz al-Asad asked several substantive questions 
which the Israeli side has to answer. Asked about the idea of 
Majdal Shams first, the foreign minister said Syria's position 
is that the Golan should be restored in full. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58128 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes084_m_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-084 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   King, al-Asad Said to Agree on Ministers' Meeting </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    King, al-Asad Said to Agree on Ministers' Meeting </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN0105120394 Amman AL-MAJD in Arabic 2 May 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> JN0105120394 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman AL-MAJD </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] In addition to extending condolences on the death of 
Her Majesty Queen Zayn al-Sharaf, the Jordanian queen mother, 
Syrian President Hafiz al-Asad's visit to Jordan on Thursday [28 
April] was a political opportunity to exchange views with Jordan 
on developments in the Arab situation and Jordanian-Syrian 
coordination on the political settlement. This is especially 
true in view of the fact that the visit coincided with U.S. 
Secretary of State Warren Christopher's regional tour and the 
announcement by Israel and the PLO that they have reached an 
agreement on the implementation of the Oslo agreement on 
self-rule in Gaza and Jericho, and that the agreement will be 
signed on Wednesday under U.S.-Egyptian sponsorship. 
  During their meeting, King Husayn and President al-Asad 
stressed adherence to a comprehensive and final solution. They 
emphasized that Syrian-Jordanian-Lebanese coordination will 
continue and that any new separate deals that would weaken other 
positions will be avoided. 
  Jordan explained that it rejected and continues to reject 
U.S. proposals on the formation of a four-way 
Egyptian-Israeli-Palestinian-Jordanian committee whose task 
would be to help implement the self-rule agreement. 
  Jordan proposed that a six-way committee be set up within 
the 
framework of the Washington negotiations to discuss appropriate 
ways to link the Palestinian self-rule agreement to other tracks 
of bilateral negotiations. 
  For this six-way committee, which would be comprised of 
representatives from Egypt, Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, the 
Palestinians, and Israel, to advance the peace negotiations on 
all tracks, including the Palestinian-Israeli agreement, Jordan 
believes that U.S. and Russian participation will be useful and 
will help bring views closer. However, the United States, 
Israel, and Egypt believe that any formula of this kind means a 
return to an international peace conference. The three parties 
believe that a solution can only be reached within a bilateral 
framework following the example of the Camp David and Oslo 
agreements. Moreover, Christopher told King Husayn that Arab 
coordination prevents parties from moving toward separate 
settlements, for bilateral negotiations are held in isolation 
from other parties and it would be faster to reach bilateral 
solutions. 
  In their meeting, which was held during a working luncheon, 
the Jordanian monarch and the Syrian president agreed that a 
meeting of the foreign ministers of the Arab parties to the 
negotiations will be held in Amman soon after the conclusion of 
the U.S. secretary of state's tour. The aim of the meeting will 
be to assess the results of this tour and to adopt a unified 
stand on the resumption of the bilateral negotiations, which are 
supposed to resume in Washington in mid-May. 
  According to both sides' assessment, the Jordanian-Syrian 
meeting was successful. It was agreed to intensify contacts to 
emphasize coordination. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58129 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes084_m_94002" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-084 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  29 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   New Measures for West Bank Arrivals Take Effect </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    New Measures for West Bank Arrivals Take Effect </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN2904142494 Amman Radio Jordan Network in Arabic 1100 GMT 
29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2904142494 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Radio Jordan Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Interior Minister Salamah Hammad has announced his 
ministry has decided to reconsider all measures pertaining to 
the arrival of West Bankers and Gazans in the country. He said 
all Interior Ministry organizations will apply new measures in 
this regard as of the day after tomorrow, Sunday [1 May]. 
  Hammad made these remarks during a tour of the al-Husayn 
Bridge this morning. During his tour, he inspected the 
reception halls for arrivals and departures. He also listened 
to the requests of arrivals from the West Bank and Gaza Strip. 
  Hammad added: Pursuant to the instructions of His Majesty 
King Husayn, and in light of the inspirational and culturally 
significant statements made by His Highness Crown Prince Hasan 
last week on the need to reconsider the regulations issued by 
the Interior Ministry with regard to the residence of West 
Bankers and Gazans in Jordan, the Interior Ministry has decided 
to thoroughly reconsider all measures and regulations issued by 
the Interior Ministry in this regard. The new measures will 
facilitate things for arrivals. 
  The interior minister said all the measures enforced thus 
far 
were intended to firmly promote the steadfastness of the 
kinsfolk in the occupied territories, safeguard Jordan's 
national security, and thwart the implementation of displacement 
schemes the Israeli occupation troops sought to carry out. 
  Hammad went on to say: The Interior Ministry has enforced 
the old regulations pertaining to the residence and transit of 
West Bankers and Gazans within the context of Jordan's firm 
pan-Arab outlook vis-a-vis the kinsfolk and brothers. Jordan, 
which was careful to keep the bridges with the occupied 
territories open since 1967, has contributed to maintaining 
pan-Arab cohesion and deepening the pan-Arab sentiments of the 
kinsfolk, who are holding out in the occupied Palestinian Arab 
territories, although this policy was the object of criticism by 
some parties in the past. 
  Hammad said: Jordan, which is proud of its Hashemite 
leadership, has striven to promote the spirit of Arab 
renaissance and sought to make Jordan an exemplary homeland that 
embraces pan-Arab sentiments, and that inspires others with its 
ideas, instead of exporting them, as His Highness Crown Prince 
Hasan has noted. 
  Jordan's historical ties with the kinsfolk in our occupied 
homeland have always required the best formula and best way to 
mitigate the agonies brought about by the occupation. 
  Hammad added: Given the fact that the reasons that prompted 
the Interior Ministry to issue its old regulations are about to 
become a thing of the past, and since the Palestinian brothers 
are about to realize their aspirations, the Interior Ministry, 
in implementation of directives issued by His Majesty King 
Husayn, will revoke these regulations. Besides, it will strive 
to reconsider the regulations governing the renewal of the 
passports carried by West Bankers and Gazans. It will also 
introduce the system of cards [not further identified]. This 
will allow for the movement of students across the bridges to 
further their education. The ministry will later announce 
additional measures in this regard. The Interior Ministry will 
thoroughly examine the usefulness of using cards. The new 
regulations will take effect as of the day after tomorrow, 
Sunday. 
  Salamah Hammad began his tour this morning by chairing a 
meeting at the Bridges Administration Office. The meeting was 
attended by the officials concerned. The interior minister 
informed them of the new regulations. He was also briefed on 
the measures the Bridges Administration Office will enforce this 
summer. 
  During the meeting, Colonel 'Abd-al-Salam al-Ja'afirah, 
director of the Bridge Security Centers, said the bridges will 
remain open for 18 hours every day, and that there will be a 
chance to make reservations ahead of the actual crossing time, 
to ease the burdens placed on citizens. He said the number of 
reservation offices in all the governorates will be increased. 
  The minister of interior also inspected the new reception 
hall, which has room for 600 passengers. He also met with 
departures and listened to their remarks. He received several 
arrivals, including a delegation of Gazans that came to offer 
condolences on the death of the late Queen Zayn al-Sharaf. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

