<H3> <TI>   Observer To Attend Disarmament Talks in Qatar </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Observer To Attend Disarmament Talks in Qatar </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   JN3004195394 Amman Jordan Television Network in English 1900 
GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN3004195394 </F>
<F P=104>  Amman Jordan Television Network </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "News at Ten" program] </F>
  [Text] Jordan will send an observer to a round of 
multilateral talks on Middle East disarmament scheduled to be 
held in Doha, Qatar, this week. Diplomatic sources said Jordan 
will continue to send low-key participants to the multilateral 
talks until action was taken on the siege of al-'Aqabah. 
  This is the second time that Jordan will be staying away 
from 
active participation in the Middle East multilateral talks since 
it announced that rejoining the talks hinged upon an end to 
interceptions by Western warships of al-'Aqabah-bound vessels. 
  The naval inspections, which are part of the enforcement of 
sanctions against Iraq, have cost the Kingdom $1.3 billion in 
extra freight and delays caused by diversions of ships from the 
port of al-'Aqabah. 

</TEXT>

