<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Spokesman Outlines Position on al-'Aqabah Blockade </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Spokesman Outlines Position on al-'Aqabah Blockade </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904144694 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 29 Apr 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM2904144694 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Agreement To Solve Problem of </F>
Jordanian al-'Aqabah Blockade"] 
  [Excerpt] Amman, AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT -- The Jordanian 
Foreign Ministry yesterday announced that the proposal currently 
raised to solve the problem of the blockade imposed on 
al-'Aqabah port, which -- so it seems -- enjoys the Americans' 
approval, is actually a Jordanian proposal. 
  In a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT, Ahmad Mubayyidin, 
spokesman for the ministry, said that the proposal says that an 
international company -- namely the British company Lloyd's 
Register, which is not a commercial company -- would inspect the 
ships and cargo in port, not at sea as is happening now. He 
denied that there is a specific date for implementing this 
proposal. He added: Of course, legally, the blockade does not 
concern the United States in particular, as it falls under the 
powers of the UN Security Council sanctions committee. Thus 
consultations must be held within the framework of this 
committee in order to take a decision to begin implementing the 
proposal, which stipulates that al-'Aqabah-bound ships should 
not be subjected to obstacles or search measures by U.S. Navy 
units or any other units, and that these ships should arrive in 
the port very easily. Cargo should be examined inside the port 
by the international company's representative in cooperation 
with a competent Jordanian committee. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

