<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Syria Said Ready To Recognize Security Needs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Syria Said Ready To Recognize Security Needs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0205140294 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1300 GMT 2 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0205140294 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] In a meeting held in the prime minister's 
bureau this afternoon, U.S. Secretary of State Christopher 
presented a detailed Syrian answer regarding the continuation of 
the negotiations. Syria insists that the withdrawal from the 
Golan Heights be complete, but it is willing to recognize 
Israel's security needs and to discuss normalization. This is 
reported by our political correspondent Shlomo Raz. [passage 
omitted] 
  [Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew at 1300 GMT on 2 May carries a 
report by Sefi Hendler on the meeting between Christopher and 
Rabin, adding that "according to what we learned from political 
sources in Jerusalem, progress was indeed achieved in talks with 
Syria. Even if it is not exceptional, this is unprecedented 
progress on the Syrian track. This is the first time since the 
beginning of the negotiations with Syria that the Syrians have 
not rejected Israel's proposals out of hand. In their meeting, 
Christopher presented to Rabin Syria's answers to the security 
issues relating to the withdrawal. This is the first time that 
Syria has addressed Israel's security needs. The Syrian 
response is currently being examined."] 
  Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin said we are at the first stages 
of our negotiations with Syria, therefore he cannot say whether 
he is optimistic or pessimistic. Our correspondent Yo'el Nir 
reports Mr. Rabin told the Labor Knesset faction Israel has not 
used Christopher's service for relaying to Syria a withdrawal 
map or the final withdrawal lines. 
  Yitzhaq Rabin said he was furious over the fact that a 
regular army battalion is forced to guard 415 Jews in Hebron 
instead of fighting terrorism. Mr. Rabin said the IDF [Israel 
Defense Forces] is being stretched to the limit in guarding the 
settlements and the Green Line instead of fighting terrorism. 
Rabin said that it is not Elon More [West Bank settlement] 
which is guarding Hadera and 'Afula, but rather the IDF. It is 
not the number of settlements on the Golan Heights which defend 
the Golan, but rather the number of tanks deployed there. 

</TEXT>

