<H3> <TI>   Rabin's Office Denies Opposition Charges on Golan </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Rabin's Office Denies Opposition Charges on Golan </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0105155094 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1500 GMT 1 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0105155094 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Two opposition leaders, the Likud's Binyamin 
Netanyahu and Refa'el Eytan of Tzomet, accused the prime 
minister of lying about the Golan Heights. Netanyahu told a Tel 
Aviv news conference that a year ago he presented a map in the 
Knesset showing the stages of withdrawal from the Golan Heights, 
and Rabin denied the remarks. Today, Netanyahu said, I have 
proof that it is precisely the map Christopher is presenting 
President al-Asad in Syria. 
  Our party affairs correspondent Shmu'el Tal reports that 
Refa'el Eytan submitted a paper offered to him as a basis for 
negotiations on his joining the coalition three months ago. He 
said the paper claims that no settlement would be uprooted, the 
Golan settlements would be strengthened, and all the completed 
apartments would be inhabited. These points were also shown to 
be false, Eytan said. 
  The prime minister's bureau said in response that there has 
not been any change in Israel's position on peace with Syria 
since the establishment of the government, and the commitment to 
hold a national referendum prior to any signing of a peace 
agreement with Syria that involves territorial concessions 
remains intact . 

</TEXT>

