<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres on Lifting Closure, Freeing Hamas Leader </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Peres on Lifting Closure, Freeing Hamas Leader </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA2904184894 Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1730 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2904184894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Israel Television Channel 1 Network 
in Hebrew 1730 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=105> Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Foreign Minister Peres by political </F>
correspondent Gadi Sukenik in the studio on 29 April -- recorded] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Sukenik] The IDF [Israel 
Defense Forces] withdrawal will be completed some two to three 
weeks after the agreement with the PLO is signed. Will the 
closure imposed on the territories be lifted? 
  [Peres] If the knives are set aside, the closure will be 
lifted. This time, however, they -- not just we -- will have an 
interest in removing the knives. They will be in charge of the 
well-being of the people. They will be in charge of their 
income, their security, and they will have to maintain relations 
with Israel that enable them to resume work in Israel. 
Previously, a Palestinian interest that focused on opposite 
goals was created. This time they have an interest in running 
their self-government. 
  [Sukenik] For example, do you foresee the possibility that 
Shaykh Ahmad Yasin, the founder of Hamas, will be released from 
prison? 
  [Peres] If Ahmad Yasin announces he is for peace and against 
violence -- and not that he opposes violence only within the 
territories, as he previously said -- I am for releasing him. 
He is an old man with paralyzed legs. All that he has left is 
a mouth and a head. If he calls on his people to stop terrorism 
and embark on the path of negotiations, we will sit with him. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

