<H3> <TI>   Commentary Views Mediation in Bosnia, Croatia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commentary Views Mediation in Bosnia, Croatia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD3004121594 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 1002 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD3004121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed commentary] </F>
  [Excerpts] Croatian Prime Minister Nikica Valentic arrived 
in our country after the arrival in Tehran of the Bosnian deputy 
prime minister. In an interview with correspondents upon 
arrival, he said: If a confederation plan for Bosnia and Croatia 
fails to succeed, the international community will pay a heavy 
price. [passage omitted] 
  The Islamic Republic of Iran, which recently has hosted 
prominent Bosnian and Croatian authorities, not only gives 
prominence to mutual economic, communications, and political 
ties with Bosnia and Croatia, but also endeavors to play the 
role of a mediator to bond the two countries of Bosnia and 
Croatia and, through bringing their stances closer together, to 
pave the way for the creation of stable and peaceful relations 
in the Balkans. [passage omitted] 
  The role played by Iran, as the closest ally and a supporter 
of the oppressed Bosnian nation, in resolving the Balkan crisis 
through efforts aimed at establishing a confederation of Bosnia 
and Croatia -- a plan that was approved by the Bosnian 
parliament three months ago -- has gained further prominence and 
is indicative of the realization of Iran's spiritual and 
diplomatic influence by its guests from the Balkans. That is 
why the Croatian prime minister has called on Iran to stop the 
recurrence of clashes, which stem from misunderstanding between 
the Croats and the Muslims, and to support the confederation 
plan. 
  Apart from the Bosnian issues, the Croatian prime minister 
will also hold talks with our country's officials on relations 
between Tehran and Zagreb. Those ties will include trade 
exchanges and economic and communications cooperation. 
Significant outcome is expected from the talks in that respect. 

</TEXT>

