<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Saudi Arabia </F>
<H3> <TI>   King Receives Yemeni Envoy, Message From Salih </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    King Receives Yemeni Envoy, Message From Salih </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3004204694 Paris AFP in English 1939 GMT 30 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3004204694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Riyadh, April 30 (AFP) -- Yemen's Planning Minister 
'Abd- al-Karim al-Iryani arrived here Saturday [30 April] with a 
message for King Fahd dealing with the situation in Yemen and a 
bilateral border dispute, officials said. 
  Al-Iryani's visit came amid reports of fresh clashes between 
rival northern and southern Yemeni troops in the 'Imran region, 
60 kilometers (36 miles) north of Sanaa. 
  The minister told AFP the message, from President 'Ali 
'Abdallah Salih, was a response to a message Salih received from 
the king 10 days ago. 
  Al-Iryani refused to comment on the conflict between forces 
loyal to Salih and those backing the president's southern rival 
'Ali Salim al-Bid. 
  A southern military spokesman in Aden said elite northern 
Republican Guards "resumed criminal actions against elements of 
the (southern) third armoured brigade." 
  Ferocious tank battles in the same area Wednesday and 
Thursday left nearly 200 dead and dozens of others wounded, 
according to journalists. 
  The Saudi-Yemeni border dispute centres on the provinces of 
'Asir, Najran and Jizan, which were handed to Saudi Arabia under 
an agreement signed in 1934. Yemen, which claims the provinces, 
says the accord expired in 1992. 
  Saudi-Yemeni relations soured following Iraq's August 1990 
invasion of Kuwait, when Yemeni leaders voiced support for Iraqi 
President Saddam Husayn. 
  Al-Iryani said the next round of bilateral talks on the 
border problem would be held in Riyadh around May 20. 

</TEXT>

