<HT>    "drnes085bb_94004" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-085 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  2 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Inter-Arab Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Arab League Secretary General Visits Libya </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Arab League Secretary General Visits Libya </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Comments on Lockerbie </H4>

<F P=102> LD0205145494 Tripoli Great Jamahiriyah Radio Network in 
Arabic 1230 GMT 2 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0205145494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tripoli Great Jamahiriyah Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpts] Dr. 'Ismat 'Abd-al-Majid, secretary general of 
the Arab League, yesterday evening held a news conference in 
Tripoli, in which he expressed his happiness at visiting the 
Great Jamahiriyah and his meeting with the brother leader of the 
revolution. He underlined the positive results achieved by this 
visit. [passage omitted] 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said that his visit to the Great 
Jamahiriyah had dealt with the so-called Lockerbie case and the 
recent development that occurred at the meeting of the Arab 
League council, at the level of Arab foreign ministers in Cairo. 
He said: At the council we achieved a unanimous Arab decision 
that the Arab League should put forward an initiative, with the 
accord of member-states, for finding a peaceful settlement of 
this artificial case. He pointed out that the idea of a trial 
at the International Court of Justice in The Hague had won the 
support of the Arab countries. Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid said that 
bringing the suspects before a neutral side accords with the 
requirements of justice and with the discovery of the truth. He 
said further: I have informed the U.S., Britain, and France of 
this decision agreed upon by the Arab League, and I have also 
informed the secretary general of the United Nations and the 
chairman of the Security Council in March. 
  He stressed that there was nothing there to justify a 
rejection by the Western states of this proposal, and he 
underlined in this respect that the position of the Great 
Jamahiriyah was founded on legitimacy and a sound legal basis 
and that we must stick to it, insist on it, and call for its 
implementation. He made clear that this issue was exhaustively 
discussed, and that when he returned to Cairo he would make 
moves in this respect. He said: We will carry on our moves 
together with our eagerness at the same time to stress the 
legitimate nature of the Libyan position and its tallying with 
international law, because the Great Jamahiriyah had tackled 
this crisis with the appropriate legal means. 
  Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid also said: Right is on our side and we 
must stick to it, insist on it and discuss it, and the coming 
stage will witness a coordination in order to explain the Arab 
viewpoint on this position, which has become an all-Arab 
position and not just that of the Great Jamahiriyah. 
  Concerning the possibility of the Arab states abandoning the 
unjust measures imposed on the Great Jamahiriyah, particularly 
now that much evidence has emerged that proved that the Great 
Jamahiriyah was innocent of this accusation, Dr. 'Abd-al-Majid 
said: The Arab countries have the power of decision in what they 
do, and he stressed that the decision taken by the recent 
meetings of the Arab League council to back and support the Arab 
Libyan position was now an all-Arab position that must be also 
taken into account by the Western sides. The secretary general 
reiterated the rejection by the Arab League of the unjust 
resolutions, and he underlined that the so-called Security 
Council had double-standards. He said: I have said frankly 
that we did not accept this style and this situation. He said: 
We will strive for a debate on this matter, and we will try all 
possibilities to refute the position of the West in this 
respect, and we will strive to clarify the issue to a number of 
the Security Council member states. This will be done in the 
coming weeks, he said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

