<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th on Talks With Israelis, Agreement </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Sha'th on Talks With Israelis, Agreement </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0205165394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1600 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0205165394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 2 May (MENA)--Dr. Nabil Sha'th, head of the 
Palestinian delegation to the Palestinian-Israeli talks aimed at 
reaching agreement on self-rule in Gaza and Jericho, has said 
the two delegations have almost completed drafting the major 
part of the agreement. He added that the Israeli withdrawal 
from self-rule areas in Gaza and Jericho will actually begin the 
day of the signing, Wednesday [4 May]. 
  In press statements today, he said the remaining issues 
concern some security arrangements in Gaza, the maritime borders 
of the self-rule authority in Gaza, and the map of Gaza. He 
noted that discussion of these issues will be completed this 
evening and that the discussion on legal jurisdiction is almost 
over. 
  Sha'th said the foreign ministers of Egypt, the United 
States, and Russia will sign the final agreement in addition to 
Palestinian president Yasir 'Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister 
Yitzhaq Rabin. 
  He affirmed that the agreement stipulates that the Israeli 
withdrawal will be completed within three weeks following the 
signing and he noted that the Israeli side has pledged to 
complete the withdrawal in two weeks. 
  He said some Israeli camps will be evacuated Thursday 
evening 
or Friday morning after the signing and that the withdrawal will 
begin the day of the signing. 
  He said a unit made up of 1,000 Palestinian policemen will 
enter Gaza and Jericho Thursday morning and that the remainder 
of the force will arrive within three weeks. 
  This force is comprised of 9,000 personnel, 7,000 of whom 
come from outside the occupied territories and 2,000 from inside. 
  Sha'th said that a Palestinian security delegation led by 
Ziyad al-Atrash will arrive in Cairo today. He noted that the 
Palestinian police are ready to enter Gaza and Jericho 
immediately after the Israeli withdrawal and denied Israeli 
claims to the contrary. 
  As for the Palestinian detainees, the Palestinian official 
said that all points concerning the timetable of their release 
have been agreed upon. He said that every Palestinian, whether 
an individual or member of a Palestinian organization, should be 
bound by the agreements and pledges to which the PLO has 
committed itself. 
  Commenting on the meeting of the committee in charge of 
detainees, Sha'th said that a meeting was held yesterday evening 
with Israeli General Yantof Sameh to draw up the timetable for 
the detainees' release. 
  In another development, sources close to negotiations have 
told MENA that the points still under discussion are related to 
territorial waters. The Palestinians demand 12 nautical miles, 
while the Israelis insist on giving them only three nautical 
miles. 
  As for mapping lands around roads, the Israelis want to set 
aside 55 meters on either side of each road that is not to be 
disposed of or built on. The Palestinians want this area to be 
35 meters on each side. 
  In another development, it has been learned that some 
40-to-50 Palestinian deportees will return to Gaza and Jericho 
the day after tomorrow, Wednesday, and that 1,000 detainees will 
be released on Thursday, the day after the autonomy agreement is 
signed. 
  It has also been learned that Israel has agreed to give the 
Palestinians 20 nautical miles for fishing purposes. The issue 
of joint patrols along parallel roads has not been settled yet. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

