<F P=100> ARABIAN PENINSULA </F>
<F P=101> Yemen </F>
<H3> <TI>   YSP Denounces Former Minister's Remarks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    YSP Denounces Former Minister's Remarks </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2604100094 London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT in Arabic 25 Apr 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> PM2604100094 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Lutfi Shatarah: "Socialist Party Demands Army </F>
Withdrawal From Seven Governorates"] 
  [Excerpt] London -- Authoritative Yemeni Socialist Party 
[YSP] sources have attacked former Foreign Minister Dr. 
'Abd-al-Karim al-Iryani for announcing the number of incidents 
and and assassinations to which the YSP has been exposed over 
the past three years. They accused him of appointing himself 
policeman, prosecutor, and judge at the same time. 
  Al-Iryani said that the YSP and its cadres have been exposed 
to nine attempts only, and that the suspects are in jail. But 
the sources stress that the incidents exceed 152. 
  Elsewhere, YSP Information Center sources in Aden have said 
that YSP representatives on the military committee continue to 
insist on the party's position urging that the Armed Forces 
withdraw from the seven governorates (Lahij, Abyan, Shabwah, 
Ma'rib, Ta'izz, Ibb, and al-Bayda') and that all military units 
be moved out of these governorates, saying that there is no 
justification for a military presence in these areas, known in 
the past as the fringes between the two parts of Yemen, except 
in the areas which represent protection for the Republic of 
Yemen. 
  In a statement to AL-SHARQ AL-AWSAT, the sources denied that 
the YSP had demanded the withdrawal of what used to be known as 
the southern and northern forces to their positions before 
unity, contrary to what has been reported by some circles in the 
General People's Congress. 
  The YSP demanded that all armed forces, wherever they are, 
be 
treated equally in terms of food, clothes, and other 
necessities. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

