<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   AL-AHRAM Views Rabin's Moscow Visit, Ties With Russia </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    AL-AHRAM Views Rabin's Moscow Visit, Ties With Russia </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC3004082594 Cairo MENA in Arabic 2255 GMT 29 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC3004082594 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 29 Apr (MENA)--AL-AHRAM newspaper says the 
purpose of Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin's visit to the 
Russian capital Moscow this week was to express Israel's wish to 
end practically a long-running estrangement with Russia, 
inheritor of the former Soviet Union. It adds that the visit 
also carries an implicit message, addressed to the Syrians and 
Palestinians in particular, that Israel can compete for their 
strategic ally if it wishes. 
  In Saturday's editorial, AL-AHRAM says during his visit 
Rabin 
convinced the Russians to agree to mediate with Syria on 
searching for missing Israelis from previous wars. In addition 
there are reports that Russian officials have promised Rabin 
that, for the time being, they will refrain from selling any 
advanced aircraft to Syria. The editorial, however, doubts that 
Russia will honor its promise because of its economic situation, 
which makes it willing to sell weapons to any buyer. 
  The paper expresses its belief that, despite several 
technical agreements signed between the two countries, there are 
factors that will limit the advancement of Russian-Israeli 
relations and their talks on cooperation in the armament sector. 
  AL-AHRAM notes that current Russian policy has revised its 
retreat from and strong stands against Arab causes that were 
adopted at the end of Gorbachev's term and right after the 
Soviet Union's collapse. Furthermore, the paper says, Israel 
has no major interest in having Russia participate forcefully in 
the region's peace process. 

</TEXT>

