<H3> <TI>   Musa Comments on Yemen, South Africa, Rwanda </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Musa Comments on Yemen, South Africa, Rwanda </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC0205142394 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1325 GMT 2 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC0205142394 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 2 May (MENA)-- Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa has 
stated that resolving Yemen's problem depends on the two parties 
to the dispute and that Egypt is following the developments and 
doing what it can. Musa said: We hope the clashes will stop, as 
President Mubarak said. He called for putting an end to armed 
clashes in order to protect Yemeni unity from disintegration. 
  Commenting on the results of the elections in South Africa, 
Musa said the African National Congress had been favored and 
expected to win the majority of votes. He remarked that this is 
a giant step in South African history because, once the 
elections are over, the road will be open to putting an end once 
and for all to racial discrimination and apartheid, so they can 
embark on a new era of democracy and majority rule. Egypt is 
looking forward to the final results and the proclamation of the 
new system in South Africa, he said. 
  Touching on the situation in Rwanda, the foreign minister 
said the situation in Rwanda is very serious and requires 
collective African action. This is what President Mubarak 
emphasized in his messages and in his contacts with the United 
Nations and the OAU, because it is primarily an African 
responsibility. But it is also an international responsibility, 
Musa said. 

</TEXT>

