<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Croatian Prime Minister Concludes Talks </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Croatian Prime Minister Concludes Talks </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Meets With Hashemi-Rafsanjani </H4>

<F P=102> LD0105105794 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0930 GMT 1 May 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD0105105794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>

<F P=105>  Persian </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] President Hashemi-Rafsanjani received the Croatian 
prime minister Nikica Valentic today. 
  At the meeting, the president stressed the need for 
strengthening solidarity and further cooperation among the 
states in the Balkan region in order to confront aggressors and 
to consolidate peace and stability in that region. Condemning 
the aggression of the Serbs against Bosnia-Herzegovina, he said: 
Undoubtedly the fates of the Balkan region states are tied 
together, and peace and friendship in the region is to the 
benefit of all those states, just as cooperation and unity in 
the face of any aggression and sectarianism are to the detriment 
of enemies and aggressors and also guarantee the future 
stability and tranquillity of the region. 
  Hashemi-Rafsanjani considered the grounds for cooperation 
between the Islamic Republic of Iran and the Republic of Croatia 
to be positive, and expressed the hope that the results of talks 
between the Croatian delegation and our country's officials 
smooth the way for further expansion of economic, commercial, 
and political ties between the two countries. 
  During the meeting, where First Deputy President Habibi was 
also present, the Croatian prime minister, declaring his 
country's support for the territorial integrity of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, described the policy of the Serbian forces - 
who are supported by the superpowers - as aggressive and said: 
In history Croats and Bosnians have fought side by side against 
aggressors and have always lived in harmony. He added: The 
Croatian Government will make all efforts to eliminate the 
slight disputes between the Muslims and Croats in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina, since peace and stability in that region 
will be to the benefit of the two nations and other states. 
  The Croatian prime minister considered the results of his 
visit to Iran to be a turning point in the bilateral ties and 
expressed the hope that through the normalization of the 
conditions in the Balkan region and the punishment of the 
Serbian aggressors in that region through international forums 
the trend of expansion of ties between the Balkan states - 
especially Croatia - with Iran is accelerated. 
  At the meeting the Croatian prime minister extended an 
official invitation from his country's president to Mr. 
Hashemi-Rafsanjani to visit that country. The president, 
accepting the invitation, expressed the hope to visit Croatia 
and Bosnia at an opportune moment when the conditions are 
normalized in those two countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

