<F P=100> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   300,000 Afghan Refugees To Return Home in 1994 </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    300,000 Afghan Refugees To Return Home in 1994 </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   LD0105141594 Tehran IRNA in English 1348 GMT 1 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD0105141594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran IRNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Mashad, Khorasan Prov., May 1, IRNA -- Some 300,000 
Afghan refugees residing in Iran will return home this year 
under a program worked out by a commission consisting of 
representatives of Iran, Afghanistan and the U.N. High 
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR). 
  According to the director general in charge of foreign 
nationals and immigration affairs at the Interior Ministry Ahmad 
Husseini, the repatriation of the refugees is to start from June 
22. 
  Husseini recently visited the Afghan province of Harat along 
with other members of the commission to inspect the status of 
Afghan refugees who have returned home. 
  He told reporters here Saturday that the outcome of a plan 
concerning the repatriation of 850,000 refugees last year and 
their integration into Afghan society was satisfactory. 
  He emphasized that the Afghan refugees who have returned 
home 
have played a key role in the reconstruction of their country 
mainly due to their theoretical and practical skills. 
  In response to the request of the Islamic Government of 
Afghanistan, Iran has issued six month long residence permits 
for some 540,000 refugees who are living in Iran without having 
identification cards, Husseini added. 
  He stressed that during his stay in Harat he announced the 
Interior Ministry's readiness to set up camps inside Afghan 
territory for accomodation of refugees in emergency cases. 

</TEXT>

