<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Mediators Seek Government-'Awn `Dialogue' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Mediators Seek Government-'Awn `Dialogue' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PM2904151294 London AL-HAYAH in Arabic 29 Apr 94 pp 1, 4 </F>
<F P=103> PM2904151294 </F>
<F P=104>  London AL-HAYAH </F>
<F P=105>  Arabic </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Bisharah Shirbil: "Contacts Pave the Way for </F>
Serious Dialogue Between the Lebanese State and 'Awn"] 
  [Excerpt] London -- Reliable sources have told AL-HAYAH 
that the Lebanese state is moving toward opening a serious 
dialogue with [former Prime Minister and Army Commander] General 
Michel 'Awn with the aim of filling the political vacuum that 
occurred after the arrest of Dr. Samir Ja'ja', commander of the 
now banned Lebanese Forces. 
  They added that "the dialogue is beginning through local and 
international mediators and Damascus is not distant from that." 
  They pointed out that "the end of Ja'ja''s role, the 
detached 
position of the Christians, and the cancellation of Pope John 
Paul II's visit to Lebanon have created the feeling that the 
current situation cannot continue as solutions in the region 
become imminent, and that peace requires internal stability and 
a strong Lebanese authority supported by the broadest sectors of 
Lebanese society." 
  The same sources emphasized that "the meeting which took 
place between 'Awn and former President Shaykh Amin al-Jumayyil 
covered the dialogue issue but there were differences of opinion 
regarding the national conference 'Awn intends to convene in 
Paris in June. Al-Jumayyil is not expected to attend that 
conference, for several reasons." 
  They added that "contacts made by mediators between 'Awn and 
the state have come a long way and the results will be known at 
the earliest possible time barring a surprise that would torpedo 
the entire process." [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

