Daily Report 
<DATE1>  4 May 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ten Killed, 80 Wounded in `Intense' Infantry Attack </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ten Killed, 80 Wounded in `Intense' Infantry Attack </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK0405113094 Hong Kong AFP in English 1113 GMT 4 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK0405113094 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [By Terence White] </F>
  [Text] Kabul, May 4 (AFP) -- At least 10 people were killed 
and 80 wounded in a brief but intense overnight infantry attack 
by rival factions battling Afghan President Borhanoddin Rabbani, 
frontline and hospital sources said Wednesday. 
  A combined infantry force of Prime Minister Golboddin 
Hekmatyar and Uzbek General Abdol Rashid Dostam based in and 
around the Old Microrayan housing estate attacked pro-Rabbani 
troops across the Kabul River in an attempt to establish a 
foothold there. 
  "The enemy's morale was too weak to sustain an infantry 
attack so they used their heavy weapons," frontline commander 
Sabor of the defending pro-Rabbani troops told AFP. 
  Speaking from his base in the new Microrayan housing estate 
facing the Uzbek opposition dug-in no more than 100 metres 
across the Kabul River, Sabor said three of his men were wounded 
while he had received a report that at least 10 of the attacking 
force had been killed. 
  The 30-minute exchange of small-arms fire was the most 
intense witnessed by locals for several weeks. Even to the rear 
of the combat zone in Wazir Akbar Khan residential area, 
incoming rounds smacked against houses like rain-drops on a tin 
roof. 
  Pro-Rabbani troops based in the apartments of the new 
Microrayan housing estate have converted what were once bedrooms 
and sitting-rooms to frontline bunkers with firing slits 
protected by massive walls of sandbags. 
  Even so, from the heights of the Uzbek-occupied Maranjan 
Hill 
behind Old Microrayan, direct hits by Dostam's heavy artillery 
gunners have broken up the steel-reinforced concrete walls of 
these four-storey apartment blocks like they were lumps of dry 
cake. 
  On Wednesday, delegates said to be representing 15 peace 
organizations met at the Intercontinental Hotel and proposed a 
unified draft aimed at ending the factional fighting in 
Afghanistan. 
  In 11 articles which rehash previously tried and failed 
proposals, the Unified Draft of the Afghan Joint Reconciliative 
Assembly calls for a ceasefire and the convening of a national 
Grand Assembly to elect a parliament and new Afghan leader. 
  While considerable thought has been given to the mechanics 
of 
selecting delegates to the National Assembly, the establishment 
of a ceasefire -- a necessary prerequisite for an election -- is 
mentioned only in passing. 
  The prospects of immediate peace in Kabul can only be 
advanced by a sincere reconciliation between the two main 
rivals, Rabbani and Hekmatyar, who until now have refused to 
come to terms with each other, observers said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-58375 </DOCNO>
