<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Release of 2,500 Palestinian Prisoners Begins </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Release of 2,500 Palestinian Prisoners Begins </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA0405113594 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1100 GMT 4 May 
94 </F>

<F P=103> TA0405113594 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>
<F P=105>  Hebrew </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] The release of the 2,500 prisoners slated to return 
home by Sunday, as stipulated in the Cairo agreement, began at 
midday today. Our correspondents Nisim Qeynan and Moti Amir 
report that seven buses carrying freed prisoners left the 
Qezi'ot detention facility and headed for the Gaza Strip, but 
were stopped at the Nahal 'Oz checkpoint. Meanwhile, a large 
crowd of relatives was waiting for the returning prisoners on 
the other side of the checkpoint. The hold-up is believed to 
have been caused by the delay in the Cairo ceremony. The buses 
with released prisoners were eventually permitted to drive on. 
  It has been learned that all the released prisoners are 
affiliated with Fatah, with the exception of two Islamic Jihad 
and two Hamas [Islamic Resistance Movement] members who signed a 
statement of support for the Declaration of Principles, and that 
about 1,000 prisoners will be released by the end of the day. 
  In Gaza city and in refugee camps in the Strip, the 
returning 
locals are being received with festive processions. In Jericho, 
local inhabitants decorated the police station with flowers and 
palm branches and hoisted a PLO flag. The city has been 
declared a closed military zone. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

